07770nam a22009495i 9781442687738DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426877387 a10.3138/97814426877382doi  a(DE-B1597)465353  a(OCoLC)979836712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aRA644.5.C66 2008 7aMED0360002bisacsh04a362.196/04400aContesting Illness :bProcess and Practices /ced. by Pamela Moss, Kathy Teghtsoonian. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- t1. Power and Illness: Authority, Bodies, and Context -- t2. Claiming a Disability Benefit as Contesting Social Citizenship -- t3. Workers’ Compensation and Controversial Illnesses -- t4. Managing Workplace Depression: Contesting the Contours of Emerging Policy in the Workplace -- t5. Contesting Coronary Candidacy: Reframing Risk Modification in Coronary Heart Disease -- t6. Hepatitis C and the Dawn of Biological Citizenship: Unravelling the Policy Implications -- t7. Tracing Contours of Contestation in Narratives about Chronic Fatigue Syndrome -- t8. Cancer as a Contested Illness: Seeking Help amid Treatment -- t9. Edging Embodiment and Embodying Categories: Reading Bodies Marked with Myalgic Encephalomyelitis as a Contested Illness -- t10. Managing the Monstrous Feminine: The Role of Premenstrual Syndrome in the Subjectification of Women -- t11. Resisting an Illness Label: Disability, Impairment, and Illness -- t12. The Race and Class Politics of Anorexia Nervosa: Unravelling White, Middle-Class Standards in Representations of Eating Problems -- t13. ‘More Labels Than a Jam Jar’: The Gendered Dynamics of Diagnosis for Girls and Women with Autism -- t14. The Female Sexual Dysfunction Debate: Different ‘Problems,’ New Drugs – More Pressures? -- t15. Moving from Settled to Contested: Transformations in the Anatomo-Politics of Breast Cancer, 1970–1990 -- t16. Environments, Bodies, and the Cultural Imaginary: Imagining Ecological Impairment -- t17. Contestation and Medicalization -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relationship between power and illness is the subject of limited discussion despite it being one of the most important issues in health-related policies and services. In an effort to correct this, Contesting Illness engages critically with processes through which the meanings and effects of illness shape and are shaped by specific sets of practices. Featuring original contributions by researchers working in a number of disciplines, this collection examines intersections of power, contestation, and illness with the aid of various critical theoretical frameworks and methodological approaches.The contributors explore experiences of illness, diagnosis, and treatment, and analyse wider discursive and policy contexts within which people become ill and engage with health care systems. Though each essay is unique in its approach, they are linked together by a shared focus on contestation as a conceptual tool in considering the relationship between power and illness. Rather than focus on a single example, the contributors address different contested illnesses (chronic fatigue syndrome and environmental illness, for instance) as well as the contested dimensions of illnesses that are accepted as legitimate such as cancer and autism. Contesting Illness offers valuable insights into the assumptions, practices, and interactions that shape illness in the twenty-first century.Contributors Jan AngusPia H. Bülow Peter ConradJoyce DavidsonHelen GremillionMaren KlawiterJoshua KelleySteve Kroll-SmithKatherine LippelPamela MossMichael OrsiniMichael J. PrinceAnnie PottsMary Ellen PurkisSharon Dale StoneCheryl StultsKatherine TeghtsoonianJan